observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the Municipal Mayor: (i) ensure that all procurement activities undertaken by the LGU is strictly in accordance with the provisions of the 2016 Revised IRR of RA No. 9184, to ensure the regularity of the procurement process and the award of the contracts; (ii) ascertain that the LGU is fully equipped and has enough capacity to implement the infrastructure projects “By Administration”, pursuant to Appendix 1 of 2016 Revised IRR of RA No. 9184; and (iii) consider procurement of common-use goods, supplies, materials and equipment from the DBM-PS.
We also recommended that the Municipal Mayor require the:
Bids and Awards Committee and the Technical Working Group to:                     (i) immediately submit all the lacking bidding documents to the Acting Municipal Accountant, for the eventual submission to the Audit Team; (ii) be cautious in the evaluation and assessment of the eligibility as to legal, technical and financial capacities of the prospective bidders; and (iii) revisit the updated GPPB guidelines, especially the latest Philippine Bidding Documents, and adopt the same in the succeeding procurements;
Municipal Engineer to: (i) ensure that detailed engineering activities on all infrastructure projects are sufficiently carried-out, such as the preparation of the plans and drawings, technical specifications, and detailed quantities and cost estimates, and the computation of the contract duration, among others, pursuant to Annex A of 2016 Revised IRR of RA No. 9184, and submit the same to the Audit Team to facilitate the Technical Audit Specialist’s (TAS’s) technical review, evaluation and inspection; (ii) closely monitor the project implementation to ensure that these are implemented in accordance with the approved plans and specifications and completed within the contract duration; (iii) ensure the accuracy of the information indicated in the Statements of Work Accomplished and Time Elapsed, and other related technical documents; and (iv) ascertain that relevant information on all infrastructure projects are duly posted on the project’s billboards, pursuant to COA Circular No. 2013-004;
Acting Municipal Accountant to: (i) immediately submit to the Audit Team the lacking supporting documents, including the contract for the purchase of one unit utility vehicle, for verification, and ensure that all claims are duly supported with proper and complete supporting documents, as required under Sections 9.1, 9.1.1, and 9.1.3 of COA Circular No. 2012-001, before processing for payment, to establish the validity, regularity and propriety of the transactions; (ii) ensure that purchases of supplies and materials are recorded under the appropriate Inventory accounts upon purchase, and expensed only upon its issuance, and  (iii) prepare the necessary JEV to account for the noted errors in recording, for fair and accurate presentation of the affected accounts in the Financial Statements;
Municipal Budget Officer to obligate the full contract cost of the projects once awarded to the winning bidders, pursuant to Section 350 of RA No. 7160, for proper reporting of obligations within the same year it was incurred, and to ensure availability of appropriations for the intended projects;
Municipal Treasurer to ascertain that all DVs are duly signed by the appropriate officials before effecting payments, see to it that payments are received by duly authorized representatives only, and require the payees and/or their authorized representatives to indicate their printed names in the Box D portion of the DVs, to facilitate verification; and
Acting Storekeeper to prepare the required RISs for all the issuances of supplies and materials to the end-users and/or target recipients, which shall be consolidated using the RSMI and submit the same to the Acting Municipal Accountant for proper recording in the books.

In view of the foregoing, we recommended that the Municipal Mayor require the:

Inventory Committee to conduct a complete physical count on all PPEs of the Municipality, submit a complete and accurate RPCPPE thereon, copy furnished the Acting Municipal Accountant for reconciliation with the accounting records, and henceforth ensure that complete physical count are strictly conducted every year; 

Acting Property Officer and the Acting Municipal Accountant to maintain a complete and proper perpetual inventory records, such as Property and Supply Cards, SLCs and PPELCs, respectively, and ensure that the same are kept updated and reconciled with Accounting records at all times;

Acting Property Officer to prepare the Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Property (IIRUP), together with the required supporting documents, to facilitate the disposal of the unserviceable items; and
Acting Municipal Accountant to: (i) evaluate and investigate the discrepancy amounting to P293,997,483.75, and reconcile the reported PPE balances in the Statement of Financial Position and the submitted RPCPPEs; (ii) provide depreciation expense for all depreciable assets; and          (iii) make the necessary adjustments to record in the books the project, Construction of Local Access Road (Tinangra Farm to Market Road) totaling P10,667,508.25, for fair and accurate presentation of the account balances in the Financial Statements.

In view of the foregoing, we recommended that the Municipal Mayor require the:

LDRRMO to prepare the LDRRMFIP every year, with complete details of the specifically identified programs and projects for disaster prevention, mitigation, and preparedness activities, including target PPAs for the unexpended balances under the Special Trust Fund, pursuant to COA Circular No. 2012-002;

LDRRM Council to: (i) ensure the optimal utilization of the LDRRMF, to strengthen and enhance the capacity and resilience of the LGU and the constituents to address and/or respond to calamities, disasters and emergencies; and                  (ii) ascertain that PPAs charged against the LDRRMF are related to the key objectives of disaster risk and management activities, pursuant to the provisions of the NDRRMC-DBM-DILG Joint Memorandum Circular No. 2013-1; 

Acting Municipal Accountant to: (i) ensure that purchases of relief items, supplies and materials are recorded under the appropriate Inventory accounts and recognize the appropriate expense accounts only upon its issuance;           (ii) transfer the CY 2020 unexpended appropriations for Capital Outlay (CO) back to the General Fund until the projects funded therefore are completed; and                     (iii) immediately submit to the Audit Team the lacking supporting documents to arrive at a decision in audit, and henceforth ensure that claims are duly supported with complete and proper documentation before processing for payment, to establish the validity and propriety of the disbursements; and

Acting Storekeeper to prepare the required RISs for all issuances of supplies and materials to end-users and/or target recipients, which shall be consolidated using the RSMI and submit the same to the Acting Municipal Accountant for proper recording in the books.

observations.reason:
The Inventory Committee still failed to conduct the complete physical count considering that fixed assets were not included in the submitted RPCPPEs as of December 31, 2020, as these had been overlooked by the Management. 

Moreover, the Designated Property Officer and the Acting Municipal Accountant still failed to maintain perpetual inventory records;

Also, the incomplete inventory records between the Acting Municipal Accountant and the Designated Property Officer prevented the timely reconciliation of the two records;

Detailed discussions are presented in the Part II of this Report.

